        </div>
        <div class="hub-cardinal-line">Direct commercial relationships HomeTest or its commissioners hold.</div>
        <div class="hub-cardinal-chips">
          <span>Framework suppliers</span><span>Acute trust partnership</span><span>Royal Mail</span><span>Pathology labs</span><span>Advisory &amp; capacity</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hub-cardinal-jump">Open page &rarr;</div>
      </a>

      <a class="hub-centre" href="HomeTest Operating Model - Ecosystem Built.html">
        <img class="hub-centre-logo" src="Assets/nhs-hometest.svg" alt="NHS HomeTest">
        <div class="hub-centre-label">The core &middot; Category 1</div>
        <div class="hub-centre-name">Built and run by HomeTest</div>
        <div class="hub-centre-line">What HomeTest builds, runs and staffs directly. The BAU team sizes around this.</div>
        <div class="hub-centre-chips">
          <span>Integration spine</span><span>Framework instrument</span><span>Pattern catalogue</span><span>IG framework</span><span>+6 more</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hub-centre-jump">Open page &rarr;</div>
      </a>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="eco-bau-note">
    <div class="eco-bau-h">Why this matters for BAU sizing</div>
    <div class="eco-bau-body">HomeTest needs to staff Category 1, hold the interface to Categories 2 and 3, manage the contracts in Category 4, and serve Category 5. Being an intelligent client across the other four categories is itself a substantial job: holding suppliers to SLA, holding consumed services to interfaces, holding regulators to timelines. The team is not <strong>everyone needed to run HomeTest</strong>; it is the orchestration core. The size question collapses around that.</div>
  </div>

